(Beginner) Quest 4 - Hedera Smart Contract Service - Hello World
Introduction
In this quest, we’ll be having hands-on experience with the first of three Hedera Network Services - the Hedera Smart Contract Service! We’ll start by going through a quick introduction to Hyperledger Besu and Hedera services integration. Then, we’ll be writing our first Hedera smart contract and deploying it to the testnet. Following which, we’ll see how we can interact with functions on the deployed smart contract.
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.

By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Describe the Hyperledger Besu EVM, gas fees, and rents in the context of Hedera
  • Describe the Hedera services integration
  • Describe the Hedera Smart Contract Service
  • Write a Hedera smart contract and deploy it to the testnet
  • Interact with a deployed smart contract on the testnet

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Hyperledger Besu EVM
Hedera uses the Hyperledger Besu Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM), an open-source, enterprise-grade Ethereum client developed under Apache 2.0. It is the first public implementation of Ethereum written in Java and provides businesses with the tools to build permissioned, private, and public Ethereum-based networks. 
It is compatible with popular Ethereum tools and offers a wide range of features for building decentralized applications (dApps). Refer here for more information regarding the Hyperledger Besu EVM.
Step 2: Gas Fee & Rents
Gas is a fee used to pay for Hedera Smart Contract Service transactions such as creating or calling a smart contract. The gas fees include the cost of EVM operations and intrinsic gas costs. If you are calling a Hedera Service transaction in your contract, an additional Hedera Service transaction gas fee will be charged. 
Rent is a recurring payment required to keep contracts active on the network, and it consists of contract auto-renewals and storage payments. Contract auto-renewals allow the user to set up a Hedera contract that will automatically renew itself at periodic intervals, such as monthly or annually. This eliminates the need for manual payments and reduces the administrative needs of keeping track of the contract’s expiration date. The contract creator can configure the duration of the contract, the renewal period, and the payment amount. 

Storage payment on Hedera allow users to rent storage space on the Hedera network and pay for it on a recurring basis. The user will specify the storage size, duration of the contract, and payment amount. Similar to contract auto-renewal, the storage payment contract will automatically renew itself at periodic intervals, ensuring that the user never runs out of storage space. The user can also configure the payment amount to match their usage. 

Note: rent is a feature that is currently NOT enabled on the network, therefore you currently do not have to worry about paying rent for your smart contracts.
Step 3: Hedera Services Integration
The Hedera Services integration with smart contracts allows you to directly interact with Hedera transactions within your Solidity contracts. By importing the corresponding Solidity libraries into your contract, you can connect to other Hedera Services and start building applications that utilize the Hedera network. This allows you to create secure and trustless smart contracts that interact directly with the Hedera ledger, giving you access to the rich set of features that the network has to offer. 
Furthermore, this allows you to create applications that are more secure and resilient, as the Hedera network uses a distributed consensus mechanism to ensure that all transactions are processed accurately and securely.

Currently, the Hedera Token Service transactions are supported by the Hedera Service integration. This integration enables you to interact with tokens on the Hedera network from your smart contract; providing support for transactions such as token associating, dissociating, minting, burning and transfering. Further releases are in the works to expand support for the remainder of the Hedera Token Services transactions.
Step 4: Hedera Smart Contract Service
As mentioned in Quest 1, there are three Hedera network services - 1/ Hedera Smart Contract Service, 2/ Hedera Token Service and 3/ Hedera Consensus Service. In this quest, we’ll be focusing on the Hedera Smart Contract Service! In particular, we’ll be using it to deploy a smart contract to the Hedera testnet and interact with its functions!
Smart contracts on Hedera are Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) compatible; this means that smart contracts on Hedera can be built using Solidity. Smart contracts on Hedera are optimized for hashgraph. With hashgraph efficiency, your contracts run fast with finality in seconds, carbon-negative energy use, and always predictable gas fees. The Hedera Token Service (covered in the next quest) and HBAR are key components that enable the execution of smart contracts.

The following are some key reasons for choosing Hedera to deploy your smart contracts:
  1. Solidity community - since Solidity is the the world’s most popular smart contract language, developers on Hedera can leverage community-driven standards, development tools, frameworks, and support
  2. Low fees - the efficiency of hashgraph allows for low gas fees. Smart contracts on Hedera run at a lower cost with less volatility than blockchain alternatives
  3. Fast transactions - user experience is greatly improved with transactions settling in seconds with finality instead of waiting for slow block confirmations
  4. Carbon negative - all smart contracts deployed on Hedera are environmentally sustainable and offset by Hedera’s carbon negative initiative
  5. Fair ordering - smart contracts are always processed in the order they are received, not based on how much gas you’re willing to pay or at the choice of a miner
  6. Optionally upgradable - when deploying a smart contract, you have the option to make it immutable or include admin keys that allows for modifying the smart contract for purposes such as bug fixes, dispute resolution, upgrade support, etc.
Step 5: Introduction to Remix IDE
For the subsequent steps of this quest, we’ll be writing and interacting with our first Hedera smart contract! We’ll be doing so with the help of the Remix Integrated development environment (IDE). An IDE is basically a software used to build applications using common developer tools in a graphical user interface. 
IDEs normally consist of a source code editor which is similar to a text editor but has features like syntax highlighting and programming language specific auto complete features. They also usually come with a debugger for testing programs as well as a local build compiler to build and package code needed before running it. Remix is a very popular open-source IDE used for writing, compiling and debugging Solidity code. 
 
First, head over to the Remix Online IDE.



The Remix IDE layout can be split into four main parts:
  • Icon Panel - Toggle between different plugins here, the Side Panel will change according to the plugin selected
  • Side Panel - The GUI corresponding to the plugin selected
  • Main Panel - This is where you’ll be writing smart contracts
  • Terminal - View results of the interactions with the plugins here
Step 6: Writing Our First Hedera Smart Contract
In this step, we’ll try to write our first Hedera smart contract! In the contracts folder, create a new file called HelloHedera.sol. Paste the code below into the empty file you just created. The Remix IDE comes with a handy code formatter tool. To use this, right click anywhere on the smart contract and press on ‘Format Code’.
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT pragma solidity >=0.7.0 <0.8.9; contract HelloHedera {   // the contract's owner, set in the constructor   address owner;   // the message we're storing   string message;   constructor(string memory message_) {     owner = msg.sender;     message = message_;   }   function set_message(string memory message_) public {     // only allow the owner to update the message     if (msg.sender != owner) return;     message = message_;   }   // return a string   function get_message() public view returns (string memory) {     return message;   } }

Here’s an overview of what’s happening in the code above. First, we define a new smart contract by the name of HelloHedera. In it, we initialise two variables - owner and message. Then in the constructor() function, which is a special function that runs only once at the point of contract deployment, we do 2 things: 1/ assign the value of owner to the address that deployed the smart contract msg.sender and 2/ assign the value of message to the message that was input as the function argument message_.

We then have 2 functions - set_message and get_message. Essentially, set_message allows the owner to update the message and the get_message function allows anyone to return the message.

Note: teaching Solidity is outside the scope of this campaign, thus we won’t go too much into detail regarding the code covered in the smart contract. However, if you would like to learn how to code in Solidity, please head to our Solidity skillpath here.
Step 7: Getting the Smart Contract ABI
Now that we’ve written our smart contract, we’ll need to compile it to get its Application Binary Interface (ABI). Essentially, ABI is the standard way to interact with smart contracts, both from outside the blockchain and for contract-to-contract interactions. Feel free to read more about ABI here.
By default, Remix should have the ‘Auto compile’ feature toggled on. Thus if you look under your workspace repository in Remix, you should see a folder called artifacts. Open it and you should see a file titled HelloHedera.json. This the corresponding ABI file of our HelloHedera.sol smart contract. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference on what you should see. Leave Remix open, we’ll be using this in the next step.

Troubleshooting: If you don’t see the artifacts folder, open the ‘SOLIDITY COMPILER’ tab by pressing on the compile icon in the the icon panel (refer to Step 5) and pressing on ‘Compile HelloHedera.sol’. The smart contract will compile and you should be able to see the artifacts folder as well as HelloHedera.json inside it.

Step 8: Preparing Project Repository
For the subsequent steps, we’ll be making use of the same project repository as we did in Quest 3. If you have yet to complete Quest 3, please finish Steps 1 to 4 of Quest 3 before proceeding with the remainder of this step. 
Now let’s begin! Create a new file called HelloHedera.json in the root directory of the project. Then, open up Remix and copy the entire content of HelloHedera.json and paste it into the empty file you just created.

Now create another file in the root directory of the project, this time let’s name it hello-hedera.js. Copy the code below and paste it into hello-hedera.js. 

const { Client } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); require("dotenv").config(); async function helloWorld() {  // Part 1 - Create connection to the Hedera network  const myAccountId = process.env.MY_ACCOUNT_ID;  const myPrivateKey = process.env.MY_PRIVATE_KEY;  if (myAccountId == null || myPrivateKey == null) {   throw new Error("Environment variables myAccountId and myPrivateKey must be present");  }  const client = Client.forTestnet();  client.setOperator(myAccountId, myPrivateKey);  // Part 2 - Store the smart contract’s bytecode on Hedera  // Part 3 - Deploy the smart contract  // Part 4a - Interact with the smart contract - get_message()  // Part 4b - Interact with the smart contract - set_message()  client.close(); } helloWorld();

If you’ve completed Quest 3, the code under Part 1 - Create connection to the Hedera network should be familiar to you. Essentially, all we’re doing here is grabbing our Hedera testnet account ID and private key from our .env file and establishing a connection with the Hedera network. As you’ll soon come to recognise, this is often the starting point for Hedera scripts!

Note: if you’re intending to launch to mainnet instead, you’ll need to replace Client.forTestnet() with Client.forMainnet(). You’ll also need to use an account that’s loaded with some mainnet HBAR tokens instead of your Hedera Developer Portal account.
Step 9: Project Overview
Before we proceed with the remainder of this quest, let’s do a little stocktake of what we’ve covered so far and what we’ll be covering in the next few steps. The typical workflow of using the Hedera Smart Contract service is as follows:
  • Part 0 - Write the smart contract and get its bytecode ✅
  • Part 1 - Create connection to the Hedera network ✅
  • Part 2 - Store the smart contract’s bytecode on Hedera
  • Part 3 - Deploy the smart contract
  • Part 4 - Interact with the deployed smart contract

So far, we’ve only accomplished Part 0 using the Remix IDE and its built-in Solidity compiler to get the smart contracts’ bytecode (can be found in HelloHedera.js) as well as Part 1 (previous step). In the next few steps, we’ll be proceeding with the remaining portion of the workflow. Let’s go!
Step 10: Storing the Smart Contract Bytecode on Hedera
As mentioned, the next step we’ll need to do is to store the smart contract’s bytecode on Hedera. We can do this using the FileCreateTransaction() API. Copy the code below and paste it under // Part 2 - Store the smart contract’s bytecode on Hedera in your script.
let helloHedera = require("./HelloHedera.json"); const bytecode = helloHedera.data.bytecode.object; const fileCreateTx = new FileCreateTransaction().setContents(bytecode); const submitTx = await fileCreateTx.execute(client); const fileReceipt = await submitTx.getReceipt(client); const bytecodeFileId = fileReceipt.fileId; console.log("The smart contract byte code file ID is " + bytecodeFileId);

We’ll also need to import the FileCreateTransaction module from the Hedera Javascript SDK. We can do so by adding it in our first line of code. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference on how your code in hello-hedera.js should look like at this point.

Now let’s break down what each line of the code does! First, we import the ABI of the smart contract and store the bytecode in the variable bytecode. Then we create a file on the Hedera network using FireCreateTransaction() and set its contents to be the bytecode of the compiled smart contract.

We then fire off the transaction to the Hedera network with the .execute() command, passing in client as its argument. To get the transaction information, we use the .getReceipt() method. Lastly, we query specifically for the fileId, which we then console log so that we can see it in the terminal output when we run the script.

Now let’s see the code in action. Open up your terminal and navigate to the root of the project directory (i.e. stackup-hedera). Then, run the command below in your terminal to run the script.

node hello-hedera.js

After running the command, you should see the file ID of the stored smart contract bytecode. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference. Now we can proceed with the next step - deploying the smart contract.

Step 11: Deploying the Smart Contract
With the smart contract bytecode stored as a file on the Hedera network, we can now deploy the smart contract and set its bytecode as the stored file. We can do this by using the ContractCreateTransaction() API. Copy the code below and paste it under // Part 3 - Deploy the smart contract in your script.
const contractTx = await new ContractCreateTransaction()   .setBytecodeFileId(bytecodeFileId)   .setGas(100000)   .setConstructorParameters(new ContractFunctionParameters().addString("Hello from Hedera!")); const contractResponse = await contractTx.execute(client); const contractReceipt = await contractResponse.getReceipt(client); const newContractId = contractReceipt.contractId; console.log("The smart contract ID is " + newContractId);

Similar to before, since we’re using two new modules - ContractCreateTransaction and ContractFunctionParameters, we’ll need to add these two to the import statement at the top of our script. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference on how your code in hello-hedera.js should look like at this point.

Let’s break it down!

As mentioned, we deploy the smart contract with the ContractCreateTransaction API. We set the file ID of the Hedera file storing the bytecode using .setBytecodeFileId(), increase gas value required for deploying the contract using .setGas() and provide the construction parameters for the contract using .setConstructorParameters() and ContractFunctionParameters(). We’ll be setting the message to “Hello from Hedera!”.

Then just like the previous step, fire off the transaction to the Hedera network with the .execute() command, passing in client as its argument. We then use the .getReceipt() method to get the receipt of the transaction, followed by querying specifically for the contractID of our newly deployed smart contract.

Let’s check it out! Run the command below in your terminal to run the script.

node hello-hedera.js

After running the command, you should see the file ID of the stored smart contract bytecode (from the previous step) as well as the smart contract ID of our newly deployed smart contract. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference. With our smart contract now deployed, we can now interact with it! Which we will do in the next step.

Step 12: Interacting With The Smart Contract - Getting the Message
In this step, we’ll be interacting with our deployed smart contract. In particular, we’ll be calling the get_message() function to return the current message stored. Copy the code below and paste it under // Part 4a - Interact with the smart contract - get_message() in your script.
const contractQuery = await new ContractCallQuery()   .setGas(100000)   .setContractId(newContractId)   .setFunction("get_message")   .setQueryPayment(new Hbar(2)); const getMessage = await contractQuery.execute(client); const message = getMessage.getString(0); console.log("The contract message: " + message);

The new modules that we’ll be using here are ContractCallQuery and Hbar. Add these to the import statement at the top of our script! Same as before, refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference on how your code in hello-hedera.js should look like.

You know the drill by now - let’s break down the code to understand what’s happening! If you recall, in the previous step when we deployed the smart contract, we set the message to be “Hello from Hedera!”. Now let’s see how we can retrieve this message with the get_message() function of the smart contract.

Since we’re simply reading stored values and not modifying the state of the contract, we can use the ContractCallQuery API. This API submits a query to the deployed contract and returns value(s), which in our case, is a message string. 

We initialize the query using ContractCallQuery, set the gas for the query to be 100000 using .setGas(), set the contract ID to query for using .setContractId(), specify the contract function which we’re interested in calling using .setFunction() and lastly, set the query payment for the node returning the request using .setQueryPayment(). Note that the value specified for the query payment must cover the cost of the request, failing which the query will not go through.

Similar to all our previous interactions with the Hedera network, we fire off the transaction using .execute() and passing in client as its argument. This time round, instead of using the usual .getReceipt() method, we use .getString(0) to get a string from the result at index 0.

Now let’s test it out! Run the command below in your terminal to run the script.

node hello-hedera.js

After running the command, you should see that in addition to the output generated from the previous steps, we now also get the value of the message variable stored in the deployed smart contract - “Hello from Hedera!”. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference.

Step 13: Interacting With The Smart Contract - Setting the Message
Now let’s try calling the set_message() function to change the stored message to something else. After doing that, let’s call the get_message() function again to return the new message. Copy the code below and paste it under // Part 4b - Interact with the smart contract - set_message() in your script.
const contractExecTx = await new ContractExecuteTransaction()   .setContractId(newContractId)   .setGas(100000)   .setFunction("set_message", new ContractFunctionParameters().addString("Hello from REPLACE-WITH-STACKUP-USERNAME")); const submitExecTx = await contractExecTx.execute(client); const receipt2 = await submitExecTx.getReceipt(client); console.log("The transaction status is " + receipt2.status.toString()); const contractCallQuery = new ContractCallQuery()   .setContractId(newContractId)   .setGas(100000)   .setFunction("get_message")   .setQueryPayment(new Hbar(2)); const contractUpdateResult = await contractCallQuery.execute(client); const newMessage = contractUpdateResult.getString(0); console.log("The updated contract message: " + newMessage);

We’ll be using one new module here - ContractExecuteTransaction. Add it to the import statement at the top of your script. Same as before, refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference on how your code in hello-hedera.js should look like.

Let’s break it down!

We can call the set_message() function of the contract by using the ContractExecuteTransaction() API. First, we set the ID of the contract we intend to interact with by using .setContractId(), then we set the gas required for the contract call using .setGas() and set the contract function to call using .setFunction(). Similar to what we did in the ContractCreateTransaction API, we use ContractFunctionParameters to specify arguments for the function call.

Replace the placeholder value passed into the function call with your StackUp username. After we’re done preparing the API call, we fire off the transaction using .execute() and we get its receipt using .getReceipt(). Recall that the .status method of a receipt will output SUCCESS if the transaction goes through successfully.

The remaining lines of code are a repeat of what we did in the previous step - calling the get_message() function to return the current message stored in the smart contract. If your code is correct, the message returned should be changed to your StackUp username.

Moment of truth, let’s see if it works! Run the command below in your terminal to run the script.

node hello-hedera.js

After running the command, you should see that the message in the contract has been updated to your StackUp username (refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference). Awesome!
Working code
const {  Client,  FileCreateTransaction,  ContractCreateTransaction,  ContractFunctionParameters,  ContractCallQuery,  Hbar,  ContractExecuteTransaction, } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); require("dotenv").config(); async function helloWorld() {  // Part 1 - Create connection to the Hedera network  const myAccountId = process.env.MY_ACCOUNT_ID;  const myPrivateKey = process.env.MY_PRIVATE_KEY;  if (myAccountId == null || myPrivateKey == null) {   throw new Error("Environment variables myAccountId and myPrivateKey must be present");  }  const client = Client.forTestnet();  client.setOperator(myAccountId, myPrivateKey);  // Part 2 - Store the smart contract’s bytecode on Hedera  let helloHedera = require("./HelloHedera.json");  const bytecode = helloHedera.data.bytecode.object;  const fileCreateTx = new FileCreateTransaction().setContents(bytecode);  const submitTx = await fileCreateTx.execute(client);  const fileReceipt = await submitTx.getReceipt(client);  const bytecodeFileId = fileReceipt.fileId;  console.log("The smart contract byte code file ID is " + bytecodeFileId);  // Part 3 - Deploy the smart contract  const contractTx = await new ContractCreateTransaction()   .setBytecodeFileId(bytecodeFileId)   .setGas(100000)   .setConstructorParameters(new ContractFunctionParameters().addString("Hello from Hedera!"));  const contractResponse = await contractTx.execute(client);  const contractReceipt = await contractResponse.getReceipt(client);  const newContractId = contractReceipt.contractId;  console.log("The smart contract ID is " + newContractId);  // Part 4a - Interact with the smart contract - get_message()  const contractQuery = await new ContractCallQuery()   .setGas(100000)   .setContractId(newContractId)   .setFunction("get_message")   .setQueryPayment(new Hbar(2));  const getMessage = await contractQuery.execute(client);  const message = getMessage.getString(0);  console.log("The contract message: " + message);  // Part 4b - Interact with the smart contract - set_message()  const contractExecTx = await new ContractExecuteTransaction()   .setContractId(newContractId)   .setGas(100000)   .setFunction("set_message", new ContractFunctionParameters().addString("Hello from REPLACE-WITH-STACKUP-USERNAME"));  const submitExecTx = await contractExecTx.execute(client);  const receipt2 = await submitExecTx.getReceipt(client);  console.log("The transaction status is " + receipt2.status.toString());  const contractCallQuery = new ContractCallQuery()   .setContractId(newContractId)   .setGas(100000)   .setFunction("get_message")   .setQueryPayment(new Hbar(2));  const contractUpdateResult = await contractCallQuery.execute(client);  const newMessage = contractUpdateResult.getString(0);  console.log("The updated contract message: " + newMessage);  client.close(); } helloWorld();

Step 14: Summary
In this quest, we’ve covered one of three of the Hedera Network Services - the Hedera Smart Contract Service. 
We wrote a Solidity smart contract using the Remix online IDE and compiled it to get its bytecode. We then created a script using the Hedera Hashgraph SDK to store the smart contract’s bytecode on the Hedera network, deployed the smart contract and interacted with its functions. 

Let’s go through a quick summary of the points covered in this quest!
  1. Hedera uses the Hyperledger Besu EVM, an open-source, enterprise-grade Ethereum client developed under Apache 2.0
  2. Gas is a fee used to pay for transactions on the Hedera Smart Contract Service
  3. Rent is a recurring payment required to keep contracts active on the network
  4. Hedera Service integration with smart contracts allows direct interaction with Hedera transactions within Solidity contracts
  5. Before deploying the smart contract, we need to first store the smart contract unto the Hedera network to get the file ID that’ll be used to deploy the contract
  6. The FileCreateTransaction() API is used to store a smart contract’s bytecode
  7. The ContractCreateTransaction() API is used to deploy a smart contract
  8. The ContractCallQuery() API is used to get a value that is stored in the smart contract
  9. The ContractExecuteTransaction() API is used to set a value to be stored in the smart contract
